    <p style="font-family:var(--font-sans); font-size:1rem; font-weight:300; line-height:1.8; color:#4a4540; margin-bottom:1.25rem;">
      I work the northern corridor regularly and understand how Chermside sits in the buyer decision. The suburb draws a diverse buyer profile. Families who want the northern corridor's convenience without sacrificing residential character find the quieter streets north and west of the Westfield precinct offer exactly that. Healthcare workers at Prince Charles Hospital make up a consistent buyer segment, particularly for apartments and townhouses close to work. Young professionals who want more space than inner-city living delivers at a reasonable price point arrive at Chermside having compared the transit options and decided the Gympie Road corridor meets their needs.
    </p>
    <p style="font-family:var(--font-sans); font-size:1rem; font-weight:300; line-height:1.8; color:#4a4540; margin-bottom:1.25rem;">
      The housing mix in Chermside is broader than most northern suburbs. There are post-war and early-contemporary detached homes on standard residential blocks, a substantial volume of units and apartments serving the rental market, and an increasing number of townhouses and medium-density developments reflecting the suburb's proximity to transit and retail. Sellers need to understand which part of that market their property occupies and which buyer profile is most likely to compete for it. The street matters enormously: a detached home on a quiet internal block well away from Gympie Road is a fundamentally different proposition to an apartment above the retail strip.
    </p>
